{"id":"2002.08166","submitter":"Yachin Ivry Prof.","authors":"Hemaprabha Elangovan, Maya Barzilay, Sahar Seremi, Noy Cohen, Yizhe\n  Jiang, Lane W. Martin and Yachin Ivry","title":"Giant Superelastic Piezoelectricity in Flexible Ferroelectric $BaTiO_3$\n  Membranes","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.app-ph cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Mechanical displacement in commonly used piezoelectric materials is typically\nrestricted to linear or biaxial in nature and to a few percent of the material\ndimensions. Here, we show that free-standing BaTiO$_3$ membranes exhibit\nnon-conventional electromechanical coupling. Under an external electric field,\nthese superelastic membranes undergo controllable and reversible\n'sushi-rolling-like' 180$^\\circ$ folding-unfolding cycles. This crease-free\nfolding is mediated by charged ferroelectric domains, leading to a giant > 3.8\nand 4.6 $\\mu$m displacements for a 30-nm thick membrane at room temperature and\n60$^\\circ$C, respectively. Further increasing the electric field above the\ncoercive value changes the fold curvature, hence augmenting the effective\npiezoresponse. Finally, it is found that the membranes fold with increasing\ntemperature followed by complete immobility of the membrane above the Curie\ntemperature, allowing us to model the ferroelectric-domain origin of the\neffect.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Feb 2020 16:29:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 24 Feb 2020 17:59:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 4 Apr 2020 12:05:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-07"}
